Note:
YAML Semantic Analyzer - Validates a YAML AST beyond grammar

The YAML parser guarantees a syntactically well-formed document and resolves
every alias (*name) to the node its anchor (&name) introduced. This pass
enforces the SEMANTIC rules a YAML consumer needs but the grammar alone does
not express:

  1. Duplicate-key policy. The YAML 1.2 spec says mapping keys must be unique;
     many real-world loaders tolerate duplicates with last-wins semantics. This
     analyzer makes the choice explicit and configurable: by default duplicate
     keys are a hard error (the safest interoperable policy), but a caller may
     opt into last-wins tolerance via the policy flag.
  2. Maximum nesting depth. Unbounded nesting is a denial-of-service vector for
     any recursive consumer; the analyzer enforces a configurable depth limit
     measured in nested mapping/sequence levels. Because YAML anchors/aliases
     can make the resolved graph share subtrees, an unresolved alias left in the
     tree is itself a structural error caught here.
  3. Structural integrity. Every node's discriminant must be one of the four
     YAML kinds, mapping nodes must carry parallel keys/children lists of equal
     length, collection nodes must carry their backing lists, and scalar nodes
     must carry a value buffer. These are invariants the parser maintains,
     validated here so a corrupted AST cannot silently reach the HIR lowering
     stage.

This mirrors the four-file frontend convention (lexer / parser / semantic /
to_hir) used by the json, dart, and fsharp frontends: the semantic analyzer is
a standalone validation stage that runs over the parser's AST before lowering.

Dependencies:
- yaml_parser.runa (for YAML AST shape and kind constants)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/yaml/yaml_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Duplicate-Key Policy Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant DUPLICATE_KEY_REJECT as Integer is 0    Note: Duplicate mapping key is a hard error (default)
Constant DUPLICATE_KEY_LAST_WINS as Integer is 1 Note: Duplicate mapping key tolerated; last occurrence wins

Note: Default maximum mapping/sequence nesting depth. Deep enough for any
Note: realistic configuration document, shallow enough to bound recursive consumers.
Constant DEFAULT_MAX_DEPTH as Integer is 512

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Analyzer State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The analyzer threads its configuration (duplicate-key policy, depth limit) and
its single-slot error channel through the recursive walk. Carrying max_depth on
the analyzer rather than as a recursion argument lets a caller tune the limit
once at construction; carrying error_message/has_error lets a deep validation
failure surface to the top-level caller without an out-parameter on every
recursive call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five 64-bit slots in declared order: error_message (owned heap NUL-terminated
string or 0), has_error boolean, duplicate_key_policy (one of the
DUPLICATE_KEY_* constants), max_depth (nesting limit), error_line (source line
of the offending node, 0 if none). Total size 40 bytes; offsets 0/8/16/24/32
are referenced directly by the analyzer Processes.
@End Implementation

Type called "YAMLSemanticAnalyzer":
    error_message as Integer        Note: Error message (owned), or 0
    has_error as Integer            Note: Boolean: 1 if a validation error occurred
    duplicate_key_policy as Integer Note: DUPLICATE_KEY_REJECT or DUPLICATE_KEY_LAST_WINS
    max_depth as Integer            Note: Maximum nesting depth permitted
    error_line as Integer           Note: Source line of the offending node (0 if none)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Analyzer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructs the analyzer with all fields zeroed except the two policy fields,
which are seeded from the caller's arguments so the default configuration
(reject duplicates, DEFAULT_MAX_DEPTH) is chosen by the caller passing those
constants rather than baked in here. error_message=0 and has_error=0 mean the
terminal success check is correct without any explicit clearing on the success
path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 40 bytes; return 0 on OOM. Zero error_message/has_error/error_line at
offsets 0/8/32; write duplicate_key_policy at offset 16 and max_depth at
offset 24 from the arguments.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_yaml_semantic_analyzer" takes duplicate_key_policy as Integer, max_depth as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create YAML semantic analyzer with the given policy and depth limit

    Let analyzer_size be 40  Note: YAMLSemanticAnalyzer: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, 0   Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, 0   Note: has_error = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, duplicate_key_policy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, max_depth
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, 0  Note: error_line = 0

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the owned error_message buffer (if any) before freeing the analyzer
record. Null-tolerant so callers may invoke it unconditionally in cleanup
paths.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If analyzer is 0, return 1. Read error_message at offset 0; if non-zero,
deallocate it. Deallocate the analyzer block. Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_yaml_semantic_analyzer" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy YAML semantic analyzer and free resources

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Latches a validation error: replaces any prior message with an owned heap copy,
sets has_error=1, and records the offending node's source line so the caller
can report a precise location. Only the first error is meaningful for callers
that stop on failure, but later overwrites are harmless because the walk
short-circuits on the first error anyway.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read offset 0 (error_message); if non-zero, deallocate. Compute msg_length via
string_length, allocate msg_length+1, memory_copy the message and NUL-terminate.
Store the buffer at offset 0, 1 at offset 8 (has_error), and the line at offset
32. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer, line as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Record a semantic validation error

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let new_error be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If new_error is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_error, message, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with new_error, msg_length, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, new_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, line

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Equality
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Mapping-key uniqueness is checked by content, not pointer identity: the parser
stores each key as a distinct heap copy, so two textually equal keys are
different pointers. A self-contained byte-comparison keeps the duplicate scan
independent of the import surface and matches the json_semantic convention.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Measure both strings via string_length; on length mismatch return 0. Otherwise
compare byte by byte; return 0 on the first mismatch, 1 if all bytes match.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_equals" takes str1 as Integer, str2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if two strings are equal by content

    Let len1 be proc string_length from StringCore with str1
    Let len2 be proc string_length from StringCore with str2

    If len1 is not equal to len2:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be 0

    While index is less than len1:
        Let char1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str1, index
        Let char2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str2, index

        If char1 is not equal to char2:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Duplicate-Key Detection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Mapping member uniqueness is checked with an explicit content comparison
(string_equals) rather than List.contains, because List.contains compares
pointer identity and every key in the parser's keys list is a distinct heap
copy. A linear scan over the keys preceding index i is the correct cost model:
YAML mappings are typically small, and a per-mapping hash set would cost more to
build than the O(n^2) scan saves for realistic member counts. The scan stops at
the first duplicate so the reported line is the earliest violation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Given the keys List and the count, for each i from 1 to count-1 compare keys[i]
against every earlier keys[j] (j from 0 to i-1) via string_equals. On the first
content match return i (the duplicate's index). Return -1 if all keys are
unique.
@End Implementation

Process called "find_duplicate_key_index" takes keys as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return the index of the first duplicate key, or -1 if none

    Let i be 1

    While i is less than count:
        Let key_i be proc get_at from List with keys, i
        Let j be 0

        While j is less than i:
            Let key_j be proc get_at from List with keys, j

            Note: A null key pointer is a structural problem, not a duplicate; skip the compare
            If key_i is not equal to 0:
                If key_j is not equal to 0:
                    Let matches be proc string_equals with key_i, key_j

                    If matches is equal to 1:
                        Return i
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Recursive Validation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single recursive validator over the four YAML node kinds. Centralising the
depth check here (incrementing only when descending into a mapping or sequence)
means scalar nesting does not count against the limit and the limit measures
true structural depth. An unresolved YAML_ALIAS reaching this pass is a parser
contract violation (the parser resolves every alias before returning), so it is
reported as a structural error rather than silently accepted. Returning 1/0
(valid/invalid) plus the latched analyzer error keeps the contract identical to
the sibling frontends' analyzers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guard the node (a null child is a structural error). Read node_type at
offset 0 and line at offset 64. For YAML_MAPPING: enforce depth+1 <= max_depth;
read keys (offset 40) and children (offset 32), require both non-null, require
equal lengths, run find_duplicate_key_index and apply the duplicate-key policy
(reject => error; last-wins => tolerate), then recurse on every child value at
depth+1. For YAML_SEQUENCE: enforce depth, read children (offset 32), require
non-null, recurse on every element at depth+1. YAML_SCALAR: require value_string
(offset 8) non-null. YAML_ALIAS: unresolved alias is a structural error. Any
unknown discriminant is a structural error. Returns 1 when the subtree is valid,
0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_yaml_node" takes analyzer as Integer, node as Integer, depth as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recursively validate one YAML AST node

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null YAML node in AST", 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 64
    Let max_depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24

    Note: Mapping validation
    If node_type is equal to YAML_MAPPING from Parser:
        Let next_depth be depth plus 1

        If next_depth is greater than max_depth:
            proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "YAML nesting depth exceeds maximum", line
            Return 0
        End If

        Let keys be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40
        Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32

        If keys is equal to 0:
            proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Mapping node missing keys list", line
            Return 0
        End If

        If children is equal to 0:
            proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Mapping node missing children list", line
            Return 0
        End If

        Let key_count be proc size from List with keys
        Let child_count be proc size from List with children

        If key_count is not equal to child_count:
            proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Mapping keys and values count mismatch", line
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Duplicate-key policy enforcement
        Let dup_index be proc find_duplicate_key_index with keys, key_count
        Let policy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16

        If dup_index is not equal to -1:
            If policy is equal to DUPLICATE_KEY_REJECT:
                proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Duplicate mapping key not allowed", line
                Return 0
            End If
            Note: DUPLICATE_KEY_LAST_WINS tolerates the duplicate; lowering keeps order
        End If

        Note: Recurse into every value at the next depth
        Let index be 0
        While index is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get_at from List with children, index
            Let child_ok be proc validate_yaml_node with analyzer, child, next_depth

            If child_ok is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Sequence validation
    If node_type is equal to YAML_SEQUENCE from Parser:
        Let next_depth2 be depth plus 1

        If next_depth2 is greater than max_depth:
            proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "YAML nesting depth exceeds maximum", line
            Return 0
        End If

        Let elements be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32

        If elements is equal to 0:
            proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Sequence node missing elements list", line
            Return 0
        End If

        Let element_count be proc size from List with elements
        Let ai be 0

        While ai is less than element_count:
            Let element be proc get_at from List with elements, ai
            Let element_ok be proc validate_yaml_node with analyzer, element, next_depth2

            If element_ok is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Set ai to ai plus 1
        End While

        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Scalar leaf: the parser always copies a value buffer (possibly empty but non-null)
    If node_type is equal to YAML_SCALAR from Parser:
        Let value_string be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8

        If value_string is equal to 0:
            proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Scalar node missing value", line
            Return 0
        End If

        Return 1
    End If

    Note:
    An alias that survived to the semantic stage was not resolved by the parser,
    which is a contract violation: the parser's resolve_aliases_in_node pass
    rewrites every YAML_ALIAS into the kind of its target before returning.
    :End Note
    If node_type is equal to YAML_ALIAS from Parser:
        proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Unresolved YAML alias in AST", line
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Any other discriminant is a corrupted AST
    proc set_semantic_error with analyzer, "Unknown YAML node type", line
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Public Validation Entry Points
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level validation over an existing AST with a caller-provided analyzer. The
root is validated at depth 0; the recursion increments depth as it descends, so
a top-level scalar document (e.g. just a number) validates at depth 0 and a
deeply nested document is bounded by max_depth. Returns the analyzer's post-walk
has_error inverted to a 1/0 valid flag so the caller has one boolean to gate
lowering on.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guard analyzer and root for null. Run validate_yaml_node(analyzer, root, 0).
Read has_error at offset 8; return 1 when has_error is 0 (valid) and 0 otherwise
(invalid). The detailed message remains on the analyzer for the caller to read.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_yaml_ast" takes analyzer as Integer, root as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate a YAML AST with an existing analyzer; returns 1 if valid

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc validate_yaml_node with analyzer, root, 0

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8

    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience facade that owns the analyzer lifecycle for callers that only want a
yes/no answer under the default policy (reject duplicate keys, DEFAULT_MAX_DEPTH).
This is the entry point a pipeline stage calls when it has no reason to override
the policy, keeping the common path a single call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guard root for null. Create an analyzer with DUPLICATE_KEY_REJECT and
DEFAULT_MAX_DEPTH; on OOM return 0. Run validate_yaml_ast, capture the result,
destroy the analyzer, and return the result.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_yaml_ast_default" takes root as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate a YAML AST under the default strict policy; returns 1 if valid

    If root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let analyzer be proc create_yaml_semantic_analyzer with DUPLICATE_KEY_REJECT, DEFAULT_MAX_DEPTH

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result be proc validate_yaml_ast with analyzer, root

    proc destroy_yaml_semantic_analyzer with analyzer

    Return result
End Process

Note: End of YAML Semantic Analyzer
